1
00:00:36,266 --> 00:00:39,060
WE ARE ALL TRYING HERE

2
00:00:42,689 --> 00:00:45,024
Why did you want to make a film
about the weather?

3
00:00:46,276 --> 00:00:47,193
I don't know.

4
00:00:47,902 --> 00:00:49,112
I have a feeling,

5
00:00:49,821 --> 00:00:50,989
but I can't explain it.

6
00:00:51,906 --> 00:00:53,074
I like that phrase.

7
00:00:53,741 --> 00:00:55,076
"I can't explain it."

8
00:00:57,161 --> 00:00:59,664
You're the first person I've met
who said they like the phrase,

9
00:01:00,206 --> 00:01:01,541
"I can't explain it."

10
00:01:03,251 --> 00:01:06,880
For over-explainers
who have to put everything into words,

11
00:01:06,963 --> 00:01:09,299
hearing that something can't be explained
is probably scary.

12
00:01:09,924 --> 00:01:10,800
But I find myself

13
00:01:11,301 --> 00:01:13,887
waking up when I hear someone admit

14
00:01:13,970 --> 00:01:15,680
they can't explain something.

15
00:01:15,763 --> 00:01:18,183
"Of course, you can't explain it."

16
00:01:19,475 --> 00:01:23,146
"How do you translate abstract thoughts
into concrete words?"

17
00:01:26,858 --> 00:01:27,942
So that's what it was.

18
00:01:28,818 --> 00:01:30,653
The gap between abstract thoughts

19
00:01:30,737 --> 00:01:32,572
and concrete words.

20
00:01:33,323 --> 00:01:34,324
Those two

21
00:01:34,949 --> 00:01:38,286
will never meet,
even if they circle the Earth 20 times.

22
00:01:39,078 --> 00:01:40,663
Even so,

23
00:01:40,747 --> 00:01:42,415
may I try to explain

24
00:01:42,498 --> 00:01:44,876
why I wanted to make a movie
about the weather?

25
00:01:46,044 --> 00:01:48,129
I find myself
wanting to explain it to someone

26
00:01:49,589 --> 00:01:51,174
who knows the limits of language.

27
00:01:52,300 --> 00:01:53,134
Okay.

28
00:01:53,927 --> 00:01:54,761
It's just

29
00:01:55,929 --> 00:01:57,055
a feeling.

30
00:02:00,350 --> 00:02:01,809
When I watch snow falling heavily

31
00:02:03,102 --> 00:02:04,687
or anything similar…

32
00:02:06,648 --> 00:02:07,482
I feel myself

33
00:02:09,025 --> 00:02:10,026
thinning out.

34
00:02:11,903 --> 00:02:12,737
You see,

35
00:02:14,030 --> 00:02:16,824
I'm the kind of person
who's entirely absorbed in myself.

36
00:02:17,867 --> 00:02:20,453
I want to cover the whole world with me.

37
00:02:21,246 --> 00:02:24,123
I want everyone to know my story.

38
00:02:25,500 --> 00:02:27,585
So I keep talking

39
00:02:27,669 --> 00:02:29,128
and talking.

40
00:02:29,212 --> 00:02:30,964
Then when it snows

41
00:02:31,047 --> 00:02:33,091
or when rain comes down in sheets,

42
00:02:33,758 --> 00:02:35,009
I thin out.

43
00:02:36,052 --> 00:02:38,888
But it's not a bad thing.

44
00:02:40,014 --> 00:02:43,184
A part of me
wants to cover the whole world with me,

45
00:02:43,977 --> 00:02:45,770
and a part of me wants to thin out.

46
00:02:47,355 --> 00:02:49,065
I think both exist in me.

47
00:02:58,491 --> 00:02:59,492
Inside me,

48
00:03:00,159 --> 00:03:03,121
there's Yeong-sil,
who wants to live an easygoing life,

49
00:03:03,705 --> 00:03:06,541
and there's Byeon Eun-a,
who wants to swing blades of revenge.

50
00:03:07,458 --> 00:03:08,292
Is it like that?

51
00:03:09,043 --> 00:03:09,877
That's right.

52
00:03:13,965 --> 00:03:15,466
"Thinning out."

53
00:03:17,218 --> 00:03:18,052
I like that phrase.

54
00:03:19,220 --> 00:03:20,138
Has your nosebleed

55
00:03:21,097 --> 00:03:22,140
thinned out?

56
00:03:23,099 --> 00:03:25,101
It disappeared a while ago.

57
00:03:27,270 --> 00:03:28,563
How's the weather today?

58
00:03:29,689 --> 00:03:31,190
Does it make you thin out?

59
00:03:32,859 --> 00:03:34,485
I'm thinning out severely.

60
00:03:35,945 --> 00:03:37,321
The traffic is terrible,

61
00:03:38,114 --> 00:03:40,158
so I'm completely stuck.

62
00:03:48,291 --> 00:03:49,584
I'm getting a call.

63
00:03:50,543 --> 00:03:51,794
I should answer it.

64
00:03:51,878 --> 00:03:53,880
Right, I'll hang up now.

65
00:03:54,714 --> 00:03:56,090
Be careful driving in the snow.

66
00:03:56,174 --> 00:03:57,216
I will.

67
00:04:08,102 --> 00:04:11,856
H-H-H-Hello?

68
00:04:11,939 --> 00:04:12,940
This is 911.

69
00:04:13,024 --> 00:04:17,111
-H-H-How far along a-a-are you?
-We're on our way.

70
00:04:17,195 --> 00:04:20,073
There was an accident on the way,
so we're taking a detour.

71
00:04:20,156 --> 00:04:20,990
You're okay, right?

72
00:04:21,491 --> 00:04:23,993
I-I-I-I'm… I'm really cold right now.

73
00:04:24,702 --> 00:04:26,829
-Can I turn on the engine?
-No, sir.

74
00:04:27,413 --> 00:04:29,082
Starting the car could cause a fire.

75
00:04:29,165 --> 00:04:30,541
-Curl up as tight as you can.
-Okay.

76
00:04:30,625 --> 00:04:32,627
Please hang in there. We'll be there soon.

77
00:04:32,710 --> 00:04:33,628
Look, I…

78
00:04:34,504 --> 00:04:35,546
I'm not…

79
00:04:36,339 --> 00:04:38,257
making these noises on purpose.

80
00:04:39,092 --> 00:04:41,886
My whole body is shaking on its own.

81
00:04:42,929 --> 00:04:45,556
How are my knees dancing like this?

82
00:04:46,682 --> 00:04:48,476
Are you sure…

83
00:04:49,894 --> 00:04:51,312
I can't turn on the engine?

84
00:04:51,896 --> 00:04:52,980
Okay, please hurry.

85
00:05:10,081 --> 00:05:11,666
Hello?

86
00:05:12,333 --> 00:05:14,419
Is anyone out there?

87
00:05:24,679 --> 00:05:27,598
BY MA JAE-YEONG, YEONG-SIL

88
00:05:34,439 --> 00:05:41,237
MA JAE-YEONG

89
00:05:41,863 --> 00:05:44,532
I-I-I-I can't…

90
00:05:44,615 --> 00:05:46,993
take a call right now.

91
00:05:47,618 --> 00:05:49,954
L-L-L-Let's talk later.

92
00:05:55,710 --> 00:05:57,003
Damn it.

93
00:06:07,221 --> 00:06:09,432
I added Byeon Eun-a's pseudonym
in the screenplay,

94
00:06:09,515 --> 00:06:12,977
so don't go around talking about it,
and keep your mouth shut.

95
00:06:13,060 --> 00:06:14,270
I'm warning you.

96
00:06:14,353 --> 00:06:16,856
If you go around running your mouth,
I won't just stand by.

97
00:06:18,900 --> 00:06:19,901
This little punk…

98
00:06:25,198 --> 00:06:27,325
-Yes?
-I know, you bastard!

99
00:06:27,408 --> 00:06:28,242
It's Yeong-sil!

100
00:06:28,826 --> 00:06:30,161
You rude bastard!

101
00:06:30,244 --> 00:06:32,371
What? "Keep your mouth shut"?

102
00:06:32,455 --> 00:06:34,165
Why do I have to keep my mouth shut?

103
00:06:34,248 --> 00:06:36,542
How am I supposed to do that?

104
00:06:36,626 --> 00:06:37,460
Hey!

105
00:06:38,169 --> 00:06:42,131
I've never kept my mouth shut in my life!

106
00:06:42,215 --> 00:06:44,800
What? What did you say?

107
00:06:44,884 --> 00:06:46,302
I'm not following.

108
00:06:46,385 --> 00:06:47,470
"I'm so sorry!"

109
00:06:48,095 --> 00:06:52,475
"Please forgive me for being a coward
and only listing her pseudonym!"

110
00:06:53,643 --> 00:06:54,602
You bastard!

111
00:06:54,685 --> 00:06:56,354
That's what you should've said, asshole!

112
00:06:57,980 --> 00:07:00,024
Why should I speak respectfully to you?

113
00:07:01,150 --> 00:07:02,777
Think about how you treated me.

114
00:07:03,527 --> 00:07:05,947
Do you know how much crap I took from you?

115
00:07:07,073 --> 00:07:08,783
I'm thankful for one thing, though.

116
00:07:09,617 --> 00:07:11,494
My blood boils whenever I think of you.

117
00:07:12,119 --> 00:07:14,372
It made me think,
"Damn it, I have to succeed

118
00:07:14,455 --> 00:07:17,750
so I can crush those worthless scumbags
and pathetic nobodies

119
00:07:17,833 --> 00:07:19,627
and shut them up for good."

120
00:07:21,420 --> 00:07:23,381
So I clenched my teeth
and fought my way to the top.

121
00:07:24,173 --> 00:07:25,091
The thing is,

122
00:07:26,008 --> 00:07:28,344
I know what kind of person you are.

123
00:07:29,345 --> 00:07:31,138
You want others to fail like you,

124
00:07:31,222 --> 00:07:32,682
so the second someone starts rising,

125
00:07:32,765 --> 00:07:35,768
you rip into them and drag them down.

126
00:07:37,645 --> 00:07:38,854
But guess what?

127
00:07:38,938 --> 00:07:40,565
Your words can't drag me down.

128
00:07:41,524 --> 00:07:42,733
But you can go ahead and try.

129
00:07:45,111 --> 00:07:46,028
Or how about this?

130
00:07:47,238 --> 00:07:49,490
Don't hold back and just come up here.

131
00:07:49,574 --> 00:07:53,369
I'll treat you with respect
when you do, okay?

132
00:07:57,081 --> 00:07:59,709
You don't even have the balls
to make it up here.

133
00:07:59,792 --> 00:08:01,711
I'm going to make it up there,
you bastard!

134
00:08:01,794 --> 00:08:04,005
Just wait, you son of a bitch!

135
00:08:06,048 --> 00:08:07,508
Just you wait!

136
00:09:12,615 --> 00:09:13,699
Sir!

137
00:09:13,783 --> 00:09:14,742
Are you okay?

138
00:09:15,368 --> 00:09:17,119
Kim, grab the gear!

139
00:09:19,664 --> 00:09:21,248
EMERGENCY SERVICES

140
00:09:24,293 --> 00:09:25,586
I'm hot.

141
00:09:25,670 --> 00:09:27,171
Sir, please lie down.

142
00:09:27,254 --> 00:09:28,130
Just lie down.

143
00:09:28,214 --> 00:09:29,465
But I'm really hot.

144
00:09:29,548 --> 00:09:31,050
-Hey, take his temperature.
-I'm hot.

145
00:09:31,133 --> 00:09:32,385
-Yes, sir.
-I'm hot.

146
00:09:52,321 --> 00:09:54,407
I almost died today.

147
00:09:54,490 --> 00:09:56,701
It snowed like crazy in Yangpyeong,

148
00:09:56,784 --> 00:09:57,993
and the car started skidding.

149
00:09:58,577 --> 00:09:59,412
Holy shit.

150
00:09:59,495 --> 00:10:01,122
It kept skidding in slow motion.

151
00:10:01,205 --> 00:10:02,623
Who knew slow motion was so scary?

152
00:10:04,667 --> 00:10:08,421
I was fighting for my life,
upside down in a -20° snowfield,

153
00:10:09,088 --> 00:10:11,215
when that asshole Ma Jae-yeong
pissed me off.

154
00:10:12,508 --> 00:10:15,344
I was determined to make it out alive.

155
00:10:16,220 --> 00:10:17,471
Everyone's asleep.

156
00:10:18,055 --> 00:10:19,473
Let's talk tomorrow.

157
00:10:20,224 --> 00:10:22,226
Go ahead and sleep.
You can read this in the morning.

158
00:10:22,309 --> 00:10:24,228
I have to finish what I was saying.

159
00:10:27,231 --> 00:10:29,817
I imagined an insanely hot summer day.

160
00:10:30,443 --> 00:10:31,569
I was super focused.

161
00:10:32,194 --> 00:10:35,406
I'm not lying when I say
that it made me sweat.

162
00:10:35,489 --> 00:10:36,866
I was sweating at -20°.

163
00:10:37,700 --> 00:10:39,201
I couldn't believe it actually worked.

164
00:10:39,285 --> 00:10:41,495
People can do things
when they're pushed to the limit.

165
00:10:42,121 --> 00:10:43,247
But you know what's even crazier?

166
00:10:45,750 --> 00:10:49,044
I must've imagined too hard
because I'm still sweating.

167
00:10:50,838 --> 00:10:53,132
I can't shut off this heat inside me.

168
00:10:56,427 --> 00:10:58,179
Hey, Dong-man!

169
00:10:58,846 --> 00:11:01,056
Hwang Dong-man!

170
00:11:01,140 --> 00:11:03,142
Let's move up!

171
00:11:04,101 --> 00:11:07,021
That damn bastard is at it again!

172
00:11:09,565 --> 00:11:11,108
You've got to be kidding me.

173
00:11:11,192 --> 00:11:13,360
He sent 300 messages.
You'd think a war broke out or something.

174
00:11:16,363 --> 00:11:17,907
Why can't he just send it all
in one long message?

175
00:11:17,990 --> 00:11:21,035
Why does he send them line by line?
It's a pain to delete them.

176
00:11:23,662 --> 00:11:24,622
Seriously.

177
00:11:24,705 --> 00:11:27,500
When can I finally stop hearing from him?

178
00:11:30,419 --> 00:11:33,714
When can I finally stop hearing you
talk crap about him while we eat?

179
00:11:34,673 --> 00:11:36,926
Whether it's 300 or 900 messages,

180
00:11:37,551 --> 00:11:39,553
just go, "Oh, he's at it again,"
and move on.

181
00:11:40,429 --> 00:11:42,181
I told you time and time again

182
00:11:42,264 --> 00:11:44,600
that anyone trashing an idiot
for being an idiot is an idiot too!

183
00:11:48,521 --> 00:11:50,022
Idiot best friends.

184
00:11:51,315 --> 00:11:52,316
You two won't split up.

185
00:11:53,484 --> 00:11:55,945
Ormy and Gasmy.

186
00:11:56,737 --> 00:11:59,573
Even your nicknames
come from the same cheap word.

187
00:11:59,657 --> 00:12:02,284
Do you know how hard I worked
to split you two up?

188
00:12:03,536 --> 00:12:04,912
You two are soulmates.

189
00:12:05,538 --> 00:12:06,705
You'll never split up.

190
00:12:09,625 --> 00:12:11,502
Just keep living like that.

191
00:12:12,628 --> 00:12:14,547
Keep talking crap about Hwang Dong-man,

192
00:12:15,422 --> 00:12:17,383
keep proving you're just like him,

193
00:12:18,634 --> 00:12:20,886
and keep living as his soulmate.

194
00:12:30,813 --> 00:12:32,147
You're saying this works?

195
00:12:32,231 --> 00:12:33,232
Good morning.

196
00:12:33,315 --> 00:12:34,775
-Good morning.
-Good morning, Ms. Ko.

197
00:12:35,776 --> 00:12:39,488
CEO KO HYE-JIN

198
00:12:45,578 --> 00:12:47,246
Good morning, Mr. Choi.

199
00:12:47,830 --> 00:12:51,083
I'm following up to see if the screenplay
I asked you to forward to Mr. Noh

200
00:12:51,166 --> 00:12:53,586
has been passed along.

201
00:12:54,169 --> 00:12:56,380
I apologize for messaging you
while you're busy,

202
00:12:56,463 --> 00:12:58,841
but I'm reaching out again
because it's urgent.

203
00:12:58,924 --> 00:13:03,262
It's imperative
that we cast him in this movie.

204
00:13:03,887 --> 00:13:05,139
The doors are opening.

205
00:13:09,226 --> 00:13:10,144
-Hi.
-Hello, sir.

206
00:13:10,227 --> 00:13:11,228
-Hello.
-Hello.

207
00:13:11,312 --> 00:13:12,354
Hi.

208
00:13:13,731 --> 00:13:14,607
Hey, Ax.

209
00:13:17,484 --> 00:13:19,278
Did you read the screenplay
sent from Kopark Film?

210
00:13:23,741 --> 00:13:25,159
-Yes.
-How is it?

211
00:13:27,411 --> 00:13:28,579
It's good.

212
00:13:29,413 --> 00:13:30,414
That's it?

213
00:13:31,874 --> 00:13:33,125
Do you not know how to elaborate?

214
00:13:35,085 --> 00:13:39,214
Should I pass this on or not?
Give it to me straight.

215
00:13:39,298 --> 00:13:40,799
Would Noh Kang-sik say yes?

216
00:13:40,883 --> 00:13:42,676
Or would he curse me out for this?

217
00:13:45,679 --> 00:13:46,639
I think it's a shame

218
00:13:47,848 --> 00:13:49,600
that a big company like ours
can't take part in it

219
00:13:50,267 --> 00:13:53,228
because it's a project
funded by the government.

220
00:13:53,312 --> 00:13:55,981
The storyline is genuinely terrifying
and completely blindsides you.

221
00:13:56,065 --> 00:13:58,150
There's no buildup and tension.

222
00:13:58,233 --> 00:14:00,569
It breaks all the basic rules of horror

223
00:14:01,362 --> 00:14:03,197
and pushes forward, full throttle.

224
00:14:03,822 --> 00:14:07,159
When it's released,
people will hesitate before opening doors,

225
00:14:07,242 --> 00:14:08,911
wondering what might be on the other side.

226
00:14:10,829 --> 00:14:12,831
It's the second-best screenplay
I've read this year.

227
00:14:13,791 --> 00:14:16,043
It'll blow the minds of veteran directors.

228
00:14:18,962 --> 00:14:19,838
Give it to me.

229
00:14:20,714 --> 00:14:22,424
Come on, give me the screenplay.

230
00:14:37,147 --> 00:14:38,524
Excuse me, Eun-a.

231
00:14:39,692 --> 00:14:40,609
Can we talk?

232
00:14:45,990 --> 00:14:48,242
Why did you agree to it?

233
00:14:49,410 --> 00:14:52,204
Why did you agree to Mr. Choi telling you
to drop out of my film?

234
00:14:52,287 --> 00:14:53,914
I'm not okay with it.

235
00:14:55,416 --> 00:14:58,210
You could've told him
that you'd discuss it with me first.

236
00:14:58,961 --> 00:15:00,045
Would that have worked?

237
00:15:01,171 --> 00:15:03,590
I enjoy watching people

238
00:15:04,216 --> 00:15:05,050
who walk all over me.

239
00:15:07,553 --> 00:15:08,637
I think to myself, "Just wait."

240
00:15:09,304 --> 00:15:11,098
"I'll make sure you end up embarrassed."

241
00:15:13,434 --> 00:15:15,144
I'm going to be very successful, you see.

242
00:15:15,978 --> 00:15:16,812
Very.

243
00:15:19,314 --> 00:15:21,108
CHEONGRAM WRITING ACADEMY

244
00:15:49,219 --> 00:15:51,096
Fix your printer already,

245
00:15:51,180 --> 00:15:53,974
instead of coming here all the time
to print out stuff.

246
00:15:54,058 --> 00:15:55,017
You know what?

247
00:15:55,768 --> 00:15:59,146
I'll still come here to teach
even after I debut and blow up.

248
00:16:00,856 --> 00:16:02,066
I won't change.

249
00:16:02,149 --> 00:16:04,735
It's fine if you change,
so please make it big.

250
00:16:04,818 --> 00:16:05,778
I'm begging you.

251
00:16:09,364 --> 00:16:12,326
KNOCK KNOCK KNOCK
BY MA JAE-YEONG, YEONG-SIL

252
00:16:16,246 --> 00:16:18,165
This screenplay is insane.

253
00:16:38,060 --> 00:16:40,479
You finally get to see the light of day.

254
00:16:47,152 --> 00:16:48,278
WOW, WHAT'S THAT?

255
00:16:50,823 --> 00:16:51,824
It's amazing, right?

256
00:16:52,407 --> 00:16:53,408
Tonight sound good?

257
00:16:54,785 --> 00:16:56,036
NODS

258
00:16:58,080 --> 00:16:58,914
CEO KO

259
00:17:01,875 --> 00:17:03,210
Hey, it's me.

260
00:17:03,293 --> 00:17:04,670
Keep a room open tonight.

261
00:17:05,587 --> 00:17:07,631
Noh Kang-sik will be coming.

262
00:17:08,215 --> 00:17:09,091
Tonight?

263
00:17:10,175 --> 00:17:11,385
Thank you.

264
00:17:12,594 --> 00:17:15,264
I was worried
I was bothering you too much.

265
00:17:15,889 --> 00:17:16,974
Thank you so much.

266
00:17:17,891 --> 00:17:19,852
Yes, I'll see you later.

267
00:17:35,826 --> 00:17:38,203
Jun-hwan, I have a favor to ask.

268
00:17:44,418 --> 00:17:46,003
Make sure Dong-man stays away

269
00:17:46,837 --> 00:17:47,796
from Agit today.

270
00:17:47,880 --> 00:17:48,881
Goddamn it.

271
00:17:48,964 --> 00:17:50,340
You're kidding me.

272
00:17:50,924 --> 00:17:51,842
What the heck?

273
00:17:51,925 --> 00:17:54,136
-Group chat!
-This is the group chat.

274
00:17:54,219 --> 00:17:55,762
-This is the group chat.
-Oh no. What do I do?

275
00:17:55,846 --> 00:17:56,680
THE EIGHT CLUB

276
00:17:57,306 --> 00:17:58,307
Where's "delete"?

277
00:17:58,390 --> 00:17:59,933
DELETE MESSAGE
DELETE FOR EVERYONE

278
00:18:00,017 --> 00:18:01,685
My goodness.

279
00:18:02,895 --> 00:18:05,439
THIS MESSAGE HAS BEEN DELETED

280
00:18:12,821 --> 00:18:14,656
WEATHER MAKER
BY HWANG DONG-MAN

281
00:18:14,740 --> 00:18:15,866
CEO KO HYE-JIN

282
00:18:17,242 --> 00:18:18,452
-Hello.
-Hello.

283
00:18:18,535 --> 00:18:19,786
So anyway…

284
00:18:19,870 --> 00:18:21,330
Noh Kang-sik is coming.

285
00:18:21,413 --> 00:18:23,498
She's trying to cast him
for Jae-yeong's film.

286
00:18:23,582 --> 00:18:24,666
Hello.

287
00:18:25,250 --> 00:18:27,961
And she knows
you're not on good terms with him.

288
00:18:30,005 --> 00:18:31,506
-Hello.
-Hello.

289
00:18:52,444 --> 00:18:57,115
Wow, losses from voice phishing
reach a trillion won a year.

290
00:18:57,199 --> 00:18:58,659
That's scary.

291
00:18:59,993 --> 00:19:01,536
Can I ask you a favor?

292
00:19:02,037 --> 00:19:03,038
Huh? What is it?

293
00:19:03,622 --> 00:19:04,748
You can say no.

294
00:19:05,749 --> 00:19:06,583
What is it?

295
00:19:09,544 --> 00:19:10,837
Would it be okay

296
00:19:11,755 --> 00:19:13,757
if I registered my grandma's address
at your place?

297
00:19:14,383 --> 00:19:15,509
What?

298
00:19:16,593 --> 00:19:17,719
Seriously, you can say no.

299
00:19:25,769 --> 00:19:26,728
Oh goodness.

300
00:19:29,564 --> 00:19:30,482
Let's go to the hospital.

301
00:19:30,565 --> 00:19:33,610
So what if I'm falling apart?

302
00:19:34,403 --> 00:19:37,447
If we can fix you before that happens,
we should get you fixed up.

303
00:19:37,531 --> 00:19:39,825
If we don't,
I'll have to carry you on my back.

304
00:19:39,908 --> 00:19:41,118
Don't be silly.

305
00:19:44,371 --> 00:19:46,498
You always carried me on your back.

306
00:19:47,499 --> 00:19:49,042
I was in elementary school,

307
00:19:50,002 --> 00:19:51,295
so why did you carry me around?

308
00:19:52,045 --> 00:19:54,006
I loved carrying kids on my back.

309
00:19:54,923 --> 00:19:57,926
It felt comforting
to feel warmth on my back.

310
00:19:59,511 --> 00:20:03,015
I wish I could've carried you on my back
when you were a baby.

311
00:20:06,351 --> 00:20:07,394
Yes?

312
00:20:08,979 --> 00:20:09,813
Two rolls of gimbap, please.

313
00:20:09,896 --> 00:20:10,772
-Okay.
-Okay.

314
00:20:17,571 --> 00:20:18,780
Here you go.

315
00:20:57,277 --> 00:20:58,695
-You're here.
-Hello.

316
00:21:02,324 --> 00:21:03,325
It's been a while.

317
00:21:03,408 --> 00:21:04,659
You're still as sexy as ever.

318
00:21:06,370 --> 00:21:07,412
Watch it.

319
00:21:09,915 --> 00:21:10,749
Where's Mr. Choi?

320
00:21:10,832 --> 00:21:12,793
-He'll be here in about ten minutes.
-Yes.

321
00:21:12,876 --> 00:21:14,544
Okay. Let's head inside.

322
00:21:19,341 --> 00:21:20,175
Thanks.

323
00:21:21,968 --> 00:21:22,803
Hey.

324
00:21:23,303 --> 00:21:26,348
What's wrong with movies
and dramas these days?

325
00:21:26,431 --> 00:21:27,474
They're boring.

326
00:21:29,226 --> 00:21:30,060
Is it just me?

327
00:21:31,061 --> 00:21:33,522
I hear even the editors
are losing their minds while editing

328
00:21:33,605 --> 00:21:34,648
because everything's boring.

329
00:21:36,233 --> 00:21:39,277
In the past, there were at least
a couple of fun releases every year.

330
00:21:39,361 --> 00:21:41,947
But now, everything feels factory-made

331
00:21:43,073 --> 00:21:44,366
and basically the same.

332
00:21:46,159 --> 00:21:47,411
How did this happen?

333
00:21:49,579 --> 00:21:51,123
Everyone is getting anxious.

334
00:21:52,833 --> 00:21:54,418
Don't get anxious.

335
00:21:55,001 --> 00:21:56,503
I miss movies

336
00:21:57,170 --> 00:21:59,673
where people talk normally.

337
00:22:03,468 --> 00:22:04,594
Is he here?

338
00:22:08,640 --> 00:22:09,474
Hey.

339
00:22:11,518 --> 00:22:12,352
Salute!

340
00:22:18,150 --> 00:22:18,984
What do you think?

341
00:22:19,067 --> 00:22:20,152
Amazing, right?

342
00:22:21,820 --> 00:22:23,029
Nice.

343
00:22:23,947 --> 00:22:25,532
Let's open it in an hour.

344
00:22:28,452 --> 00:22:29,828
It only takes an hour to read.

345
00:22:29,911 --> 00:22:31,496
Let's drink first and read after.

346
00:22:31,580 --> 00:22:32,873
KNOCK KNOCK KNOCK
BY MA JAE-YEONG, YEONG-SIL

347
00:22:32,956 --> 00:22:35,375
The title is really lame, right?

348
00:22:35,959 --> 00:22:37,711
But the content is really awesome.

349
00:22:37,794 --> 00:22:40,505
If you miss out on this,
you'll regret it forever.

350
00:22:40,589 --> 00:22:41,882
As soon as I read this…

351
00:22:43,341 --> 00:22:44,426
My heart's still pounding.

352
00:22:45,010 --> 00:22:48,054
I messaged you as soon as I read it
so that no one could snatch it up.

353
00:22:48,138 --> 00:22:50,223
There's never been a character like this
in South Korea,

354
00:22:50,307 --> 00:22:51,141
and there never will be.

355
00:22:51,224 --> 00:22:53,226
You'll thank me after you read it.

356
00:22:53,310 --> 00:22:54,895
Thank me?

357
00:22:55,937 --> 00:22:57,022
Just don't bow to me.

358
00:22:57,105 --> 00:22:58,106
Oh, please.

359
00:23:01,735 --> 00:23:05,447
Have I ever tricked you
with something like this?

360
00:23:14,915 --> 00:23:15,749
Where's the director?

361
00:23:17,167 --> 00:23:18,585
You didn't call Ma Jae-yeong?

362
00:23:18,668 --> 00:23:20,879
The director should be here!
Tell him to hurry over.

363
00:23:20,962 --> 00:23:22,047
Okay.

364
00:23:31,348 --> 00:23:32,349
It's me.

365
00:23:33,141 --> 00:23:33,975
Where are you?

366
00:23:39,356 --> 00:23:41,608
Hey, the meat is done. Eat some.

367
00:23:42,359 --> 00:23:44,361
Does Noh Kang-sik
still beat up younger actors?

368
00:23:44,444 --> 00:23:47,113
I heard when a junior acts well,
he takes them outside and beats them,

369
00:23:47,197 --> 00:23:48,907
then pressures the director
not to use that take.

370
00:23:48,990 --> 00:23:51,618
With so many people hit,
it's a miracle he hasn't been canceled.

371
00:23:51,701 --> 00:23:55,038
If a top-tier actor gets canceled,
then everyone is screwed.

372
00:23:55,121 --> 00:23:58,541
There's no one besides Noh Kang-sik
who can fill theaters these days.

373
00:23:59,084 --> 00:24:00,710
How did Ma Jae-yeong get so lucky?

374
00:24:00,794 --> 00:24:02,629
He's working with Noh Kang-sik
in his debut film.

375
00:24:11,012 --> 00:24:12,097
What am I going to do?

376
00:24:13,556 --> 00:24:15,100
I feel sick to my stomach.

377
00:24:15,850 --> 00:24:17,727
It really hurts.

378
00:24:17,811 --> 00:24:19,354
When someone does well,

379
00:24:19,980 --> 00:24:22,607
I really feel sick to my stomach.

380
00:24:24,776 --> 00:24:26,027
Jeez, my stomach.

381
00:24:26,695 --> 00:24:28,863
How can someone be so…

382
00:24:30,282 --> 00:24:31,408
one-dimensional?

383
00:24:31,491 --> 00:24:33,535
I can't believe your stomach hurts
when you're jealous.

384
00:24:33,618 --> 00:24:35,954
You punk, you were the same way
when we debuted.

385
00:24:36,037 --> 00:24:38,415
You practically
lived in the bathroom for days.

386
00:24:38,498 --> 00:24:39,833
We wouldn't care if we did well.

387
00:24:39,916 --> 00:24:41,626
Who here had a successful debut film?

388
00:24:41,710 --> 00:24:42,627
We all tanked.

389
00:24:42,711 --> 00:24:45,213
I'm even jealous that you tanked.

390
00:24:45,297 --> 00:24:47,465
I'm even jealous that you get slammed
for making a bad movie.

391
00:24:47,549 --> 00:24:50,468
Guys like me,
who've never been in the ring before,

392
00:24:50,552 --> 00:24:53,096
get jealous of stories
about getting slammed and tanking.

393
00:24:55,849 --> 00:24:56,683
I wish…

394
00:24:57,767 --> 00:24:59,936
I could get slammed too. Jeez, my stomach.

395
00:25:01,771 --> 00:25:03,606
You piss me off the most, you asshole.

396
00:25:03,690 --> 00:25:05,775
When everyone was debuting
one after another

397
00:25:05,859 --> 00:25:07,444
and only the two of us were left,

398
00:25:07,527 --> 00:25:11,740
we spent so many nights
trashing everyone in The Eight Club.

399
00:25:11,823 --> 00:25:13,033
You blew me off the second you debuted,

400
00:25:13,658 --> 00:25:14,784
along with the others.

401
00:25:14,868 --> 00:25:17,412
You still blow me off. Do you know that?

402
00:25:21,333 --> 00:25:23,209
-Hey, that's enough.
-I can't.

403
00:25:23,293 --> 00:25:24,669
I can't eat or drink anymore.

404
00:25:26,212 --> 00:25:27,380
Jeez, my stomach.

405
00:25:35,055 --> 00:25:36,348
Wait up. I'll drive you home.

406
00:25:36,431 --> 00:25:37,474
It's okay. I'll just go on my own.

407
00:25:38,058 --> 00:25:39,309
You said your stomach hurts!

408
00:25:46,566 --> 00:25:48,360
Did we commit a crime or something?

409
00:25:48,443 --> 00:25:51,696
Can we stop coddling
Hwang Dong-man already?

410
00:25:51,780 --> 00:25:54,657
Put yourself in his shoes, you punk.

411
00:25:54,741 --> 00:25:57,410
If you were the last one left
without debuting,

412
00:25:57,494 --> 00:25:59,412
wouldn't this situation sting?

413
00:26:00,121 --> 00:26:01,998
Even the junior he used to belittle

414
00:26:02,624 --> 00:26:04,417
is about to move ahead of him.

415
00:26:06,044 --> 00:26:07,462
He's experiencing

416
00:26:08,838 --> 00:26:11,800
the sorrow of the survivor,
you little jerk.

417
00:26:29,150 --> 00:26:30,318
-Welcome.
-It's fun.

418
00:26:30,402 --> 00:26:31,236
Hey.

419
00:26:32,320 --> 00:26:33,279
Hey!

420
00:27:24,873 --> 00:27:25,748
Knock, knock.

421
00:27:26,916 --> 00:27:27,750
Hey.

422
00:27:29,961 --> 00:27:31,004
Are you done reading?

423
00:27:31,671 --> 00:27:33,214
What do you think? It's amazing, right?

424
00:27:35,633 --> 00:27:38,261
How did I end up with a life like this?

425
00:27:39,929 --> 00:27:42,098
A life where I'm first to get
a good screenplay.

426
00:27:47,812 --> 00:27:49,063
Who's the director again?

427
00:27:50,064 --> 00:27:51,691
Hey, Director Ma!

428
00:27:51,774 --> 00:27:52,734
Come in.

429
00:27:53,735 --> 00:27:54,569
Introduce yourself.

430
00:27:57,280 --> 00:27:58,823
Nice to meet you.

431
00:27:58,907 --> 00:27:59,949
My name is Ma Jae-yeong.

432
00:28:03,203 --> 00:28:04,162
Nice to meet you.

433
00:28:05,914 --> 00:28:07,373
I can tell from a handshake

434
00:28:08,082 --> 00:28:09,959
whether you're a man of substance or not.

435
00:28:18,551 --> 00:28:19,511
Nicely done.

436
00:28:20,845 --> 00:28:22,138
Take a seat.

437
00:28:22,222 --> 00:28:23,056
Okay.

438
00:28:27,936 --> 00:28:29,395
Please let it slide today.

439
00:28:30,438 --> 00:28:32,190
Fighting won't get you two anywhere.

440
00:28:32,774 --> 00:28:34,776
One thing I'll give you is that

441
00:28:35,860 --> 00:28:37,695
you don't associate with indecent people.

442
00:28:38,696 --> 00:28:40,490
So why Ma Jae-yeong?

443
00:28:41,199 --> 00:28:43,201
Am I dating him or something?

444
00:28:44,828 --> 00:28:47,080
My revised draft turned out really well.

445
00:28:48,706 --> 00:28:51,209
I wanted to give it to you first,

446
00:28:51,835 --> 00:28:53,294
but I don't think I can do that

447
00:28:54,921 --> 00:28:56,130
with Ma Jae-yeong nearby.

448
00:28:58,299 --> 00:29:01,803
Dealing with two people who clash
means I won't die a natural death.

449
00:29:01,886 --> 00:29:04,222
Dealing with you and Park Gyeong-se
aged me by ten years back then.

450
00:29:05,890 --> 00:29:07,892
If I die,
you'll find holy relics in my remains.

451
00:29:07,976 --> 00:29:10,645
You know, I always take a backseat.

452
00:29:10,728 --> 00:29:13,773
Ten years ago,
I took a backseat to Park Gyeong-se.

453
00:29:13,857 --> 00:29:15,859
Now, I'm taking a backseat
to Ma Jae-yeong.

454
00:29:16,484 --> 00:29:17,402
Dong-man.

455
00:29:18,736 --> 00:29:20,238
Listen carefully to the facts.

456
00:29:21,447 --> 00:29:24,659
You both applied for the same grant,
but Ma Jae-yeong got it, and you didn't.

457
00:29:25,285 --> 00:29:27,704
The judges selected his screenplay
by unanimous decision.

458
00:29:28,413 --> 00:29:29,747
Do you want a list of the judges?

459
00:29:30,790 --> 00:29:31,749
Jae-yeong's screenplay

460
00:29:32,417 --> 00:29:33,543
is good.

461
00:29:34,377 --> 00:29:36,296
He didn't see anyone for years

462
00:29:36,379 --> 00:29:39,257
and clenched his teeth so hard
while writing that five fell out.

463
00:29:39,340 --> 00:29:41,342
You can tell he treated it
like his last chance

464
00:29:41,426 --> 00:29:42,385
and gave it his all.

465
00:29:43,845 --> 00:29:45,972
You're free to hate whoever you want,

466
00:29:46,848 --> 00:29:49,684
but don't ruin something
someone poured everything into.

467
00:29:50,727 --> 00:29:53,730
-It'll end in a killing.
-Yeong-sil probably wrote it!

468
00:29:54,606 --> 00:29:56,232
Not that I know who Yeong-sil is.

469
00:29:57,692 --> 00:30:00,445
-Recognizing talent is also a talent.
-I see.

470
00:30:01,404 --> 00:30:04,115
Like the way Gyeong-se leans on you?

471
00:30:06,242 --> 00:30:09,120
I was just as good as Gyeong-se.

472
00:30:09,203 --> 00:30:11,956
If you had backed me
the way you backed Gyeong-se,

473
00:30:12,957 --> 00:30:14,417
I would've made it already.

474
00:30:16,669 --> 00:30:18,129
Aren't you embarrassed

475
00:30:18,212 --> 00:30:20,006
that people trash his films?

476
00:30:20,089 --> 00:30:22,091
Why, that little…

477
00:30:22,675 --> 00:30:23,509
You know what?

478
00:30:24,761 --> 00:30:26,387
I respect Park Gyeong-se.

479
00:30:28,723 --> 00:30:29,933
He keeps writing

480
00:30:30,558 --> 00:30:31,517
and keeps creating.

481
00:30:32,435 --> 00:30:34,312
He takes the ridicule and keeps going.

482
00:30:34,938 --> 00:30:37,440
He cries for days
with tears and snot running down his face.

483
00:30:37,523 --> 00:30:39,734
Then he steps into the ring again.

484
00:30:39,817 --> 00:30:40,944
He gets pummeled again, thinking,

485
00:30:41,027 --> 00:30:44,238
"Maybe one day,
I'll be able to fight for real and win."

486
00:30:44,322 --> 00:30:47,408
He gets his ass kicked
but keeps getting back into the ring.

487
00:30:48,201 --> 00:30:50,495
You think people only watch movies, right?

488
00:30:50,578 --> 00:30:51,996
They see and sense energy too and think,

489
00:30:52,080 --> 00:30:55,249
"Wow, he's really trying to
see this through to the end."

490
00:30:57,543 --> 00:30:58,378
But you?

491
00:31:00,171 --> 00:31:01,172
You won't make it to the end.

492
00:31:04,592 --> 00:31:05,551
From now on,

493
00:31:06,386 --> 00:31:07,971
don't trash Park Gyeong-se in front of me.

494
00:31:33,579 --> 00:31:35,331
Hey, you know what?

495
00:31:35,415 --> 00:31:37,917
-I can die happy today.
-Good.

496
00:31:38,001 --> 00:31:39,836
I have you by my side.

497
00:31:40,712 --> 00:31:42,130
Good, good.

498
00:31:42,213 --> 00:31:43,715
-Thank you so much, Kang-sik!
-Not at all.

499
00:31:45,383 --> 00:31:46,592
I'm heading out.

500
00:31:46,676 --> 00:31:47,510
-Good night.
-Take this.

501
00:31:47,593 --> 00:31:48,720
Thank you.

502
00:31:50,346 --> 00:31:51,305
Hello.

503
00:31:55,977 --> 00:31:58,187
Can I get a handshake?

504
00:31:58,730 --> 00:32:02,316
Please shake my hand once
and see what I'm like.

505
00:32:07,822 --> 00:32:08,823
Okay.

506
00:32:14,245 --> 00:32:15,288
Relax your grip.

507
00:32:16,039 --> 00:32:17,415
Do you always shake hands like this?

508
00:32:22,754 --> 00:32:24,505
Wait, wait, I give up.

509
00:32:24,589 --> 00:32:25,506
My wrist!

510
00:32:25,590 --> 00:32:26,466
Wait a second!

511
00:32:30,553 --> 00:32:32,138
Build your core strength.

512
00:32:35,975 --> 00:32:36,934
I'm off.

513
00:32:37,018 --> 00:32:38,561
-Get home safely!
-Thanks.

514
00:32:43,149 --> 00:32:44,192
Good night!

515
00:32:49,906 --> 00:32:51,074
Jeez.

516
00:32:52,825 --> 00:32:54,786
Learn some restraint.

517
00:32:54,869 --> 00:32:57,789
How can someone not know when to refrain?

518
00:32:57,872 --> 00:32:58,873
Please refrain!

519
00:33:00,333 --> 00:33:02,376
From giving me a lecture.

520
00:33:02,460 --> 00:33:03,753
That idiot.

521
00:33:04,337 --> 00:33:06,839
If you keep that up,
you'll be attending your own funeral!

522
00:33:11,427 --> 00:33:14,889
There should be lines
that make an actor come alive,

523
00:33:15,473 --> 00:33:17,266
but I didn't see a single one.

524
00:33:18,810 --> 00:33:19,894
All right.

525
00:33:19,977 --> 00:33:21,604
Try revising it one more time.

526
00:33:37,036 --> 00:33:37,995
Let's hear it.

527
00:33:39,330 --> 00:33:41,999
Why are you refusing the money
and the house?

528
00:33:42,083 --> 00:33:43,918
I changed my grandmother's address.

529
00:33:45,002 --> 00:33:47,004
Even if reporters find out about her,

530
00:33:47,630 --> 00:33:48,923
they won't come to our home.

531
00:33:49,006 --> 00:33:50,007
So what?

532
00:33:50,925 --> 00:33:52,510
You're just going to keep living there?

533
00:33:53,386 --> 00:33:54,679
Even if the chances are slim

534
00:33:55,263 --> 00:33:58,349
that people find out you're my daughter…

535
00:34:00,434 --> 00:34:03,813
I'm asking you to live in a way
that won't make me look bad.

536
00:34:03,896 --> 00:34:05,606
Is it just that
you don't want to do it for me?

537
00:34:05,690 --> 00:34:07,817
Do you just want me to catch backlash?

538
00:34:08,401 --> 00:34:09,652
I'm not asking for anything difficult.

539
00:34:10,153 --> 00:34:13,739
Everyone would love to have a nice house
and nice clothes.

540
00:34:15,032 --> 00:34:17,410
And while we're at it,
you might as well date a more decent guy.

541
00:34:17,493 --> 00:34:19,954
Hwang Dong-man is a decent man.

542
00:34:24,333 --> 00:34:25,334
By your standards.

543
00:34:25,418 --> 00:34:26,878
Of course, I'd date someone
based on my standards.

544
00:34:26,961 --> 00:34:28,504
Do you expect me to date someone
based on yours?

545
00:34:28,588 --> 00:34:30,339
What's so decent about him?

546
00:34:30,423 --> 00:34:31,465
I'm curious.

547
00:34:33,843 --> 00:34:34,844
What makes him decent?

548
00:34:36,262 --> 00:34:37,889
I feel safe with him.

549
00:34:39,015 --> 00:34:42,101
He'd be crying in pain,
then shake it off and bounce back.

550
00:34:44,562 --> 00:34:45,521
It hits me.

551
00:34:47,356 --> 00:34:49,609
"Oh, it's possible
to bounce back like that."

552
00:34:50,610 --> 00:34:52,028
"But why am I still struggling…

553
00:34:54,030 --> 00:34:55,698
with what happened in the past?"

554
00:35:02,288 --> 00:35:03,664
Watching him gives me strength

555
00:35:04,415 --> 00:35:07,501
and gives me hope
that I can bounce back like that one day.

556
00:35:09,253 --> 00:35:11,005
I'm not sure that day
will ever come, though.

557
00:35:13,507 --> 00:35:16,510
Giving me money
and dictating how I spend it

558
00:35:17,136 --> 00:35:18,137
is crossing the line.

559
00:35:18,763 --> 00:35:20,014
Do you think I need clothes?

560
00:35:21,766 --> 00:35:24,477
My grandma's the one who saved me
when I was barely hanging on.

561
00:35:25,811 --> 00:35:28,272
After Dad died, I got nosebleeds,
fearing I'd be abandoned again.

562
00:35:29,732 --> 00:35:30,900
She'd tell me, "I'm not going anywhere."

563
00:35:32,401 --> 00:35:33,444
"I won't leave you."

564
00:35:35,446 --> 00:35:37,949
She reassured me
while she fed and clothed me.

565
00:35:39,492 --> 00:35:41,744
When I have money,
I'm going to treat her to good food.

566
00:35:43,537 --> 00:35:45,331
If there's a machine
that'll make her healthy,

567
00:35:45,414 --> 00:35:47,583
I'll sell everything I own
to put her in that machine.

568
00:35:49,794 --> 00:35:51,295
If I can spend your money like that,
I'll take it.

569
00:35:56,175 --> 00:35:58,219
Go ahead. Spend it as you wish.

570
00:36:10,064 --> 00:36:12,400
You think your past is some kind of
badge of honor?

571
00:36:12,483 --> 00:36:14,277
You think your pain
is something to flaunt about?

572
00:36:21,909 --> 00:36:23,953
What about the nine-year-old Oh Jeong-hui,

573
00:36:24,036 --> 00:36:26,455
who grew up in a family
that bought rice in plastic bags

574
00:36:26,539 --> 00:36:28,874
and once stood crying under the eaves
after one burst in the rain,

575
00:36:28,958 --> 00:36:30,751
unable to go home?

576
00:36:31,335 --> 00:36:32,670
What if her first memory

577
00:36:32,753 --> 00:36:36,549
is of her drunk father
slamming a kitchen knife into the table?

578
00:36:38,718 --> 00:36:40,678
I've never said anything like this before.

579
00:36:42,138 --> 00:36:44,640
I hate even the thought
of bringing this up.

580
00:36:45,558 --> 00:36:47,852
What is it to you
that you cherish it so much?

581
00:36:47,935 --> 00:36:50,354
You act as if it's a precious memory!

582
00:36:54,358 --> 00:36:55,234
Pain?

583
00:36:57,611 --> 00:36:59,322
Do you know what real pain is?

584
00:37:05,828 --> 00:37:08,247
It's when your dad
went back to his first love!

585
00:37:41,155 --> 00:37:42,323
Should we get going?

586
00:38:03,010 --> 00:38:04,678
What did Ms. Ko Hye-jin say?

587
00:38:04,762 --> 00:38:05,971
Did she read your screenplay?

588
00:38:07,681 --> 00:38:08,808
I didn't give it to her.

589
00:38:10,810 --> 00:38:11,936
Why not?

590
00:38:12,561 --> 00:38:13,437
She said she won't work with me.

591
00:38:15,481 --> 00:38:16,315
Why?

592
00:38:20,194 --> 00:38:22,238
She said she can't handle
two people who clash.

593
00:38:23,531 --> 00:38:24,657
You see,

594
00:38:25,282 --> 00:38:26,992
I'm not on good terms with Ma Jae-yeong.

595
00:38:35,084 --> 00:38:35,918
Is it okay

596
00:38:36,669 --> 00:38:37,503
if I talk trash?

597
00:38:42,299 --> 00:38:43,634
Yeong-sil, you little brat.

598
00:38:47,596 --> 00:38:49,515
Why did you pour everything into it?

599
00:38:49,598 --> 00:38:53,310
Do talented people just dump their talent
anywhere without holding back?

600
00:38:53,394 --> 00:38:55,271
Do ideas just keep coming?

601
00:38:56,230 --> 00:38:58,566
Why did you waste your talent
on a jerk like him?

602
00:38:59,150 --> 00:39:00,901
Why are you letting that jerk use you?

603
00:39:02,820 --> 00:39:04,196
That's why you get nosebleeds.

604
00:39:09,869 --> 00:39:10,703
I'm sorry.

605
00:39:19,712 --> 00:39:21,088
I'm sorry.

606
00:39:21,839 --> 00:39:23,257
I'm really sorry.

607
00:39:23,841 --> 00:39:25,759
I think I lost my mind for a second.

608
00:39:25,843 --> 00:39:28,220
Wait, Eun-a.

609
00:39:28,304 --> 00:39:29,388
I'm so sorry.

610
00:39:30,055 --> 00:39:31,056
Eun-a.

611
00:39:37,688 --> 00:39:39,273
Do you hold back when you date someone?

612
00:39:40,649 --> 00:39:42,568
Is that how you've been dating people?

613
00:39:43,527 --> 00:39:45,029
If you get used, then so be it.

614
00:39:45,946 --> 00:39:47,823
Do you set a daily limit on getting used?

615
00:39:48,407 --> 00:39:52,077
You should give everything you can
and then more, even if it kills you!

616
00:39:59,585 --> 00:40:00,461
Eun-a.

617
00:40:35,788 --> 00:40:36,830
Hello?

618
00:40:38,958 --> 00:40:40,417
Tell me a funny story.

619
00:40:50,261 --> 00:40:51,470
Thank you.

620
00:40:59,103 --> 00:41:01,021
I know you have one.

621
00:41:02,189 --> 00:41:04,316
Why didn't you tell me about the accident?

622
00:41:06,819 --> 00:41:08,112
Because I wanted to be cool.

623
00:41:09,738 --> 00:41:12,866
If that were my last call with you,

624
00:41:14,118 --> 00:41:15,494
I wanted to be cool.

625
00:41:52,531 --> 00:41:53,574
What do you think?

626
00:41:57,161 --> 00:41:58,203
The moment

627
00:41:59,913 --> 00:42:01,707
you start using words like

628
00:42:02,666 --> 00:42:04,335
"death," "grief," or "pain" in a poem,

629
00:42:04,877 --> 00:42:06,170
it's no good.

630
00:42:15,638 --> 00:42:19,350
Since you absolutely refuse
to give a lecture,

631
00:42:19,433 --> 00:42:21,310
they asked me to arrange a meal with you.

632
00:42:22,978 --> 00:42:24,772
They all say they're your fans, Jin-man.

633
00:42:24,855 --> 00:42:26,690
Come on, help me save face.

634
00:42:40,204 --> 00:42:42,915
We've heard so much from the professor.

635
00:42:42,998 --> 00:42:45,334
He said you were unrivaled in grad school.

636
00:42:45,417 --> 00:42:47,961
People who write good poetry

637
00:42:48,045 --> 00:42:50,714
usually struggle to write a good thesis,

638
00:42:50,798 --> 00:42:52,716
but he said yours was exceptional.

639
00:42:53,342 --> 00:42:55,386
Why aren't you writing?

640
00:42:56,011 --> 00:42:58,681
Many people are waiting
for your poetry book.

641
00:43:03,018 --> 00:43:06,146
I like your poems because they're simple.

642
00:43:06,230 --> 00:43:08,107
They're simple, but powerful.

643
00:43:08,732 --> 00:43:12,194
It makes me wonder
how something so simple can hit so deeply.

644
00:43:13,112 --> 00:43:14,530
It's not actually simple.

645
00:43:14,613 --> 00:43:17,241
When it's carefully refined,
it just feels natural.

646
00:43:18,367 --> 00:43:21,036
My poem goes downhill
the moment I start polishing it.

647
00:43:21,120 --> 00:43:22,454
It's not as good as the first.

648
00:43:23,497 --> 00:43:26,208
How do you get good at refining writing?

649
00:43:29,294 --> 00:43:31,797
Have you seen Hwang Sol-mae's latest book?

650
00:43:31,880 --> 00:43:34,466
His poetry reminds me of yours,
Mr. Hwang.

651
00:43:34,550 --> 00:43:36,260
They're simple and straightforward.

652
00:43:36,760 --> 00:43:40,222
That kind of poetry isn't simple.
It's just bad.

653
00:43:40,305 --> 00:43:43,642
I can't believe poetry books like that
sell tens of thousands of copies.

654
00:43:44,810 --> 00:43:47,604
I heard you read
the entire dictionary three times.

655
00:43:47,688 --> 00:43:50,315
Can you tell me which one it is?

656
00:43:50,941 --> 00:43:52,568
There are so many publishers, you see.

657
00:43:53,944 --> 00:43:54,862
What's your purpose?

658
00:43:56,613 --> 00:43:59,950
What's your purpose in going as far as
reading a whole dictionary to write?

659
00:44:00,659 --> 00:44:02,703
Well, obviously,

660
00:44:02,786 --> 00:44:05,164
it's to write good poetry.

661
00:44:05,247 --> 00:44:07,583
I said purpose, not goal.

662
00:44:08,709 --> 00:44:10,210
What comes after, "You wrote well"?

663
00:44:11,128 --> 00:44:13,672
Is there really a purpose in this?

664
00:44:13,756 --> 00:44:16,175
You just write because you want to,

665
00:44:16,258 --> 00:44:18,343
the way you eat when you're hungry.

666
00:44:19,678 --> 00:44:22,806
You eat because if you don't, you'll die.

667
00:44:24,141 --> 00:44:25,267
Will you die if you don't write?

668
00:44:31,064 --> 00:44:32,149
You can't write a diary

669
00:44:33,859 --> 00:44:36,028
unless you can imagine

670
00:44:37,279 --> 00:44:39,448
someone reading it someday.

671
00:44:39,531 --> 00:44:41,116
It's the hope of being read.

672
00:44:42,618 --> 00:44:46,997
All writing begins
with the hope of being read.

673
00:44:47,998 --> 00:44:48,916
That disgusting hope…

674
00:44:50,667 --> 00:44:52,211
to be seen.

675
00:44:54,922 --> 00:44:56,757
I know a poet…

676
00:45:02,596 --> 00:45:04,056
who lost their child

677
00:45:05,807 --> 00:45:07,100
and turned to alcohol.

678
00:45:09,061 --> 00:45:11,271
One day, a brilliant line of poetry
came to them,

679
00:45:11,355 --> 00:45:13,148
and they scribbled it down on paper.

680
00:45:14,107 --> 00:45:15,651
That's how the poet came to write

681
00:45:15,734 --> 00:45:18,529
what critics still consider
their best poem.

682
00:45:19,988 --> 00:45:21,198
But afterward…

683
00:45:23,200 --> 00:45:24,826
they quit writing poetry.

684
00:45:27,829 --> 00:45:29,456
Their child was gone…

685
00:45:32,084 --> 00:45:35,671
yet they got excited
over a brilliant line of poetry,

686
00:45:36,588 --> 00:45:37,756
and it disgusted them.

687
00:45:43,178 --> 00:45:44,596
That's beautiful.

688
00:45:47,641 --> 00:45:48,559
What's beautiful?

689
00:45:50,102 --> 00:45:51,353
Which part do you find beautiful?

690
00:45:51,937 --> 00:45:55,357
Their child is gone, and they get excited
over a line of poetry?

691
00:45:55,440 --> 00:45:57,025
How is that beautiful?!

692
00:46:04,032 --> 00:46:04,866
Jin-man!

693
00:46:06,451 --> 00:46:08,120
I'll drive you back.

694
00:46:08,745 --> 00:46:09,580
Jin-man!

695
00:46:19,756 --> 00:46:23,844
On clear days, I remember the words,
"I'll come and get you"

696
00:46:25,137 --> 00:46:26,430
A child and their mother

697
00:46:27,347 --> 00:46:28,599
A dog and its owner

698
00:46:29,349 --> 00:46:30,726
A window filling with light

699
00:46:33,353 --> 00:46:34,438
It's Sunday

700
00:46:35,355 --> 00:46:36,940
People pass by

701
00:46:38,108 --> 00:46:40,110
I hope they're on their way
To pick someone up

702
00:46:40,902 --> 00:46:43,280
Or on their way to meet someone

703
00:46:47,534 --> 00:46:48,577
Because they're two different places

704
00:46:49,202 --> 00:46:51,163
Because it'll be different from this place

705
00:46:52,331 --> 00:46:53,498
I believe they are

706
00:47:05,344 --> 00:47:06,511
How much was it again?

707
00:47:07,137 --> 00:47:08,472
The money you got from the KFA.

708
00:47:09,014 --> 00:47:09,848
Three billion won.

709
00:47:11,767 --> 00:47:12,934
That's not much.

710
00:47:14,227 --> 00:47:15,354
Return it.

711
00:47:16,271 --> 00:47:17,105
Excuse me?

712
00:47:17,689 --> 00:47:18,649
Just return

713
00:47:19,608 --> 00:47:20,609
that money.

714
00:47:22,861 --> 00:47:23,862
Ms. Ko.

715
00:47:25,364 --> 00:47:26,657
Let's produce this ourselves.

716
00:47:27,240 --> 00:47:29,034
We'll bring in a top-tier cast,

717
00:47:29,117 --> 00:47:31,495
lock it in as a tentpole
for the second half of next year,

718
00:47:31,578 --> 00:47:33,038
and scale it big

719
00:47:33,664 --> 00:47:34,748
to cash in big.

720
00:47:35,624 --> 00:47:39,670
I'll guarantee at least triple the profit
Kopark Film would make going solo.

721
00:47:41,004 --> 00:47:43,006
This is so sudden.

722
00:47:44,466 --> 00:47:46,301
What would we tell the KFA?

723
00:47:46,385 --> 00:47:48,136
We can make up some excuse.

724
00:47:49,429 --> 00:47:51,682
Maybe say the director
decided to back out or something.

725
00:47:52,849 --> 00:47:56,103
If I fall out with the KFA,
I'll never get government-funded projects.

726
00:47:57,062 --> 00:48:00,357
Come on, why are you trying to
survive off something like that?

727
00:48:00,440 --> 00:48:04,277
You're looking at a deal that could
wipe out your debt and get you a building,

728
00:48:04,361 --> 00:48:07,280
so why are you aiming small,

729
00:48:07,364 --> 00:48:09,324
especially when you always
worry about payroll?

730
00:48:11,243 --> 00:48:12,661
Is this about moral purity?

731
00:48:13,662 --> 00:48:14,871
It's time for Kopark Film

732
00:48:16,039 --> 00:48:16,957
to level up.

733
00:48:17,749 --> 00:48:19,459
I'll take you to the next level.

734
00:48:20,335 --> 00:48:21,420
We'll split the profits

735
00:48:21,503 --> 00:48:23,505
nine to one.

736
00:48:24,881 --> 00:48:27,134
The one I'm carving out for you

737
00:48:27,217 --> 00:48:31,179
will be worth far more than anything
Kopark Film would pull in solo.

738
00:48:31,263 --> 00:48:32,347
I guarantee it!

739
00:48:35,726 --> 00:48:37,602
The thought alone makes you smile, right?

740
00:48:38,228 --> 00:48:39,062
Let's be honest.

741
00:48:41,148 --> 00:48:42,149
What have you done?

742
00:48:42,232 --> 00:48:44,609
Ma Jae-yeong worked his ass off
to win the grant,

743
00:48:44,693 --> 00:48:48,196
and he chose your company,
so you got everything handed to you.

744
00:48:49,406 --> 00:48:50,365
I think…

745
00:48:51,283 --> 00:48:52,451
we'll take it from here.

746
00:48:53,410 --> 00:48:54,619
And we don't need Noh Kang-sik.

747
00:48:54,703 --> 00:48:56,163
The director said he'd work with me.

748
00:48:59,291 --> 00:49:00,584
Of course, I'd choose Kopark Film.

749
00:49:01,960 --> 00:49:03,128
I'm excited to be here.

750
00:49:04,254 --> 00:49:07,716
When I asked how he felt about
working with Choi Film instead…

751
00:49:09,634 --> 00:49:11,595
he said he'd be grateful.

752
00:49:12,846 --> 00:49:15,515
Look, the odds are already
stacked against you.

753
00:49:15,599 --> 00:49:17,100
Just take my offer.

754
00:49:18,059 --> 00:49:19,352
I'll make you money.

755
00:49:20,353 --> 00:49:22,481
Let's make some money, Pro Ko!

756
00:49:29,237 --> 00:49:30,238
All right.

757
00:49:34,034 --> 00:49:37,245
I'm sure you've heard
that I started out as a journalist.

758
00:49:37,829 --> 00:49:38,830
Yes, of course.

759
00:49:38,914 --> 00:49:42,292
I wasn't sure I could make it in film,
so I started as a broadcast journalist.

760
00:49:43,585 --> 00:49:45,253
During my probation period,

761
00:49:45,337 --> 00:49:48,089
I had to hunt for stories everywhere,
including police stations.

762
00:49:49,633 --> 00:49:50,717
There was a day

763
00:49:51,343 --> 00:49:52,886
when I couldn't find anything.

764
00:49:53,553 --> 00:49:56,681
When I called to say there was nothing,
my boss asked,

765
00:49:57,432 --> 00:49:59,726
"Where are you?
What do you see right now?"

766
00:50:01,061 --> 00:50:01,978
I said, "A university hospital."

767
00:50:02,604 --> 00:50:04,731
They told me to go inside, so I did.

768
00:50:05,357 --> 00:50:06,775
And they said,
"Go inside the funeral hall."

769
00:50:07,400 --> 00:50:08,485
"Who died?"

770
00:50:09,611 --> 00:50:11,488
I said, "They're all ordinary people."

771
00:50:11,571 --> 00:50:13,615
Then my boss asked,
"Do you see any unusual deaths?"

772
00:50:14,908 --> 00:50:16,451
There was one young child.

773
00:50:17,035 --> 00:50:19,120
And they said, "Go inside."

774
00:50:19,704 --> 00:50:23,333
"Go inside and ask the parents
how the kid died."

775
00:50:27,671 --> 00:50:30,549
I started swearing.

776
00:50:32,008 --> 00:50:34,469
"I said I can't do it,
you fucking bastard!"

777
00:50:35,262 --> 00:50:37,013
"I won't do this shit, asshole."

778
00:50:38,223 --> 00:50:39,599
"I'm going to do something fun."

779
00:50:40,225 --> 00:50:42,102
"Something really fun."

780
00:50:42,978 --> 00:50:46,565
"I'm going to make something so fun
even grieving parents will be

781
00:50:46,648 --> 00:50:49,025
doubled over laughing, you bastard!"

782
00:50:53,780 --> 00:50:54,698
And then

783
00:50:55,907 --> 00:50:57,117
I quit.

784
00:51:00,453 --> 00:51:02,581
I joined this industry
to do something fun,

785
00:51:03,915 --> 00:51:07,252
but the same kind of scumbag is here,
like at the news desk back then.

786
00:51:11,798 --> 00:51:13,133
I'm going to live a fun life.

787
00:51:14,009 --> 00:51:16,970
And I'm cutting ties with you,
you dirty scumbag.

788
00:51:18,471 --> 00:51:19,973
You can have it all.

789
00:51:20,557 --> 00:51:21,683
Knock yourself out.

790
00:51:26,313 --> 00:51:27,689
Come on, Ms. Ko.

791
00:51:27,772 --> 00:51:30,317
You can't do business
by acting on your feelings.

792
00:51:37,991 --> 00:51:41,161
My grandmother used to say
cooking while angry makes food taste bad.

793
00:51:42,162 --> 00:51:45,498
She always pressed her palms together
before cooking.

794
00:51:52,839 --> 00:51:55,425
When she was feeling good,
she'd grab a radish from the garden

795
00:51:55,508 --> 00:51:57,719
and whip together a soup.

796
00:51:57,802 --> 00:52:00,555
And it was delicious
even though it was a simple recipe!

797
00:52:00,639 --> 00:52:01,681
Feelings?

798
00:52:01,765 --> 00:52:03,099
They matter!

799
00:52:03,183 --> 00:52:05,018
I make movies with that in mind,

800
00:52:05,101 --> 00:52:06,937
so people watching feel good too!

801
00:52:13,693 --> 00:52:15,236
Thank you for everything.

802
00:52:17,656 --> 00:52:19,658
You have a long way to go.

803
00:52:19,741 --> 00:52:22,327
That temper of yours
is why you can't make money.

804
00:52:23,286 --> 00:52:26,081
Who the hell in this country
goes into filmmaking to make money?

805
00:52:26,164 --> 00:52:27,582
You do it for fun!

806
00:53:12,002 --> 00:53:13,461
After quitting,

807
00:53:14,087 --> 00:53:16,047
I went home and bawled.

808
00:53:16,840 --> 00:53:18,675
Then I got a text from Park Gyeong-se.

809
00:53:20,802 --> 00:53:22,220
He sent me a screenplay

810
00:53:23,805 --> 00:53:24,723
and asked me to read it.

811
00:53:24,806 --> 00:53:26,725
I sent you a screenplay. Can you read it?

812
00:53:30,603 --> 00:53:32,022
The screenplay I read

813
00:53:33,440 --> 00:53:34,858
was The Lustful Bottle Opener.

814
00:53:50,623 --> 00:53:52,667
THE LUSTFUL BOTTLE OPENER

815
00:53:54,919 --> 00:53:56,212
Then I called him and said…

816
00:53:58,089 --> 00:53:58,923
Gyeong-se.

817
00:54:04,095 --> 00:54:05,013
I love you.

818
00:54:08,058 --> 00:54:10,185
When you see something really good,

819
00:54:11,644 --> 00:54:14,898
the words "I love you" just slip out.

820
00:54:17,108 --> 00:54:19,110
What happened to the man

821
00:54:20,403 --> 00:54:22,238
who used to write words…

822
00:54:25,533 --> 00:54:27,619
that could make a crying woman…

823
00:54:29,746 --> 00:54:31,164
burst into laughter?

824
00:54:33,541 --> 00:54:35,710
That man is dead.

825
00:55:18,878 --> 00:55:21,631
So what's the best screenplay
you've read this year?

826
00:55:25,135 --> 00:55:27,554
You said Knock knock knock
was the second-best.

827
00:55:28,805 --> 00:55:29,639
So what's the best?

828
00:55:30,765 --> 00:55:32,267
Weather Maker.

829
00:55:32,851 --> 00:55:33,977
What maker?

830
00:55:35,645 --> 00:55:36,604
Weather.

831
00:55:37,230 --> 00:55:38,439
The one by Director Hwang Dong-man.

832
00:55:44,195 --> 00:55:46,030
Goodness gracious.

833
00:55:46,114 --> 00:55:47,407
The revision turned out well.

834
00:55:48,074 --> 00:55:49,951
It's on a whole new level
from the first draft.

835
00:55:51,452 --> 00:55:52,495
Listen carefully.

836
00:55:53,329 --> 00:55:55,874
There are many types of abilities.

837
00:55:55,957 --> 00:55:59,586
A director with an amazing blueprint
can have so-so results.

838
00:55:59,669 --> 00:56:03,256
A director with a so-so blueprint
can bring decent results.

839
00:56:03,339 --> 00:56:04,841
Now, what does this mean?

840
00:56:05,842 --> 00:56:08,678
It means writing isn't even one-tenth
of a director's abilities.

841
00:56:09,262 --> 00:56:11,556
What matters most
is the ability to deliver.

842
00:56:11,639 --> 00:56:16,186
Someone who can handle 200 unruly people,
grit their teeth, and hit the finish line.

843
00:56:17,979 --> 00:56:19,772
Why launch a ship that's going to sink?

844
00:56:19,856 --> 00:56:20,690
First floor.

845
00:56:20,773 --> 00:56:21,608
Jeez.

846
00:56:22,483 --> 00:56:24,402
I'm the only one who's kind enough
to tell you this.

847
00:56:25,945 --> 00:56:27,280
I'm teaching you a lot.

848
00:56:40,627 --> 00:56:43,004
Hey, Hwang Dong-man.

849
00:56:43,087 --> 00:56:45,715
I saw you took a nice crap online.

850
00:56:46,341 --> 00:56:47,592
What was it again?

851
00:56:47,675 --> 00:56:52,263
"Exposing Choi Film's exploitation
of small, powerless production companies."

852
00:56:52,347 --> 00:56:55,558
If you did something wrong,
you have to accept the backlash.

853
00:57:04,442 --> 00:57:07,195
You know what incompetent people
in this field have in common?

854
00:57:08,238 --> 00:57:09,155
It's that

855
00:57:10,323 --> 00:57:11,824
they don't even consider

856
00:57:12,784 --> 00:57:14,494
that this might not be their path.

857
00:57:14,577 --> 00:57:17,080
Capable people
think about it countless times.

858
00:57:17,163 --> 00:57:20,041
But incompetent people don't.

859
00:57:20,124 --> 00:57:22,794
Why? Because they've never
had to stake their lives on anything.

860
00:57:23,378 --> 00:57:28,591
Only people who have pushed themselves
to their limits and truly faced them

861
00:57:29,217 --> 00:57:30,510
can say the words,

862
00:57:31,386 --> 00:57:33,429
"Maybe this isn't my path."

863
00:57:33,513 --> 00:57:34,764
Am I wrong?

864
00:57:34,847 --> 00:57:38,851
People like you
who spend their lives just dabbling…

865
00:57:40,562 --> 00:57:41,771
Whatever.

866
00:57:41,854 --> 00:57:45,441
Even if your path is long and rough,
keep dabbling your way through it.

867
00:57:46,651 --> 00:57:47,569
A few days ago,

868
00:57:48,403 --> 00:57:49,862
something happened to me.

869
00:57:49,946 --> 00:57:52,907
Man, I'm bored already.
Do I have to listen to this?

870
00:57:52,991 --> 00:57:55,076
I listened to you, so now it's your turn.

871
00:57:55,702 --> 00:57:58,830
My car flipped over on a snowy road,
and I couldn't get out.

872
00:57:58,913 --> 00:58:00,873
I couldn't even turn on the engine
because I was afraid it might explode,

873
00:58:00,957 --> 00:58:02,333
so I just sat there shivering.

874
00:58:02,417 --> 00:58:04,544
And then I imagined
a scorching hot summer day.

875
00:58:04,627 --> 00:58:06,921
I'd read somewhere that it works,

876
00:58:07,005 --> 00:58:08,298
and it actually did.

877
00:58:08,881 --> 00:58:10,925
Even at -20°, I was sweating.

878
00:58:11,926 --> 00:58:15,221
As you can see, I'm still sweating.

879
00:58:15,305 --> 00:58:16,389
Go see a doctor.

880
00:58:16,472 --> 00:58:19,642
But I often catch myself
practicing acceptance speeches.

881
00:58:19,726 --> 00:58:21,269
I don't do it on purpose.

882
00:58:21,352 --> 00:58:25,523
It happens while I'm brushing my teeth
or riding the bus.

883
00:58:25,607 --> 00:58:29,444
If I'm still sweating
from briefly imagining something,

884
00:58:29,527 --> 00:58:31,779
will the acceptance speech
I've practiced for 20 years

885
00:58:31,863 --> 00:58:33,990
just scatter like dust in the wind?

886
00:58:35,700 --> 00:58:37,201
You're really messed up.

887
00:58:37,869 --> 00:58:40,747
You should see a psychiatrist
while you're at the hospital.

888
00:58:40,830 --> 00:58:42,790
And delete that post
if you don't want to get sued.

889
00:58:42,874 --> 00:58:44,334
I'm not deleting it.

890
00:58:44,417 --> 00:58:45,835
Delete it, you idiot!

891
00:58:47,670 --> 00:58:50,506
You're practicing acceptance speeches
for when you get famous,

892
00:58:51,215 --> 00:58:53,134
and you post crap like that online?

893
00:58:53,217 --> 00:58:54,886
You can get canceled over an old post.

894
00:58:54,969 --> 00:58:55,928
Delete it, you idiot.

895
00:58:56,012 --> 00:58:57,930
I did it because nobody else can!

896
00:58:58,931 --> 00:59:02,185
I did it because everyone's afraid
of a piece of trash like him!

897
00:59:04,062 --> 00:59:07,148
You punk, I've had enough of this.

898
00:59:07,231 --> 00:59:08,358
"A piece of trash"?

899
00:59:28,211 --> 00:59:29,379
Who wants napa cabbage?

900
00:59:40,014 --> 00:59:40,848
Is he a thug?

901
00:59:46,229 --> 00:59:47,605
Jeez.

902
00:59:50,692 --> 00:59:51,526
Your trunk.

903
00:59:52,819 --> 00:59:53,861
I'm good, thanks.

904
00:59:53,945 --> 00:59:54,904
Open it.

905
00:59:56,155 --> 00:59:57,365
I live alone, so no thanks.

906
00:59:57,448 --> 00:59:58,825
I said open it.

907
01:00:13,089 --> 01:00:14,006
Take two.

908
01:00:24,976 --> 01:00:26,519
-That's it.
-That's it?

909
01:00:31,566 --> 01:00:32,734
-What? 20 billion won?
-Yeah.

910
01:00:32,817 --> 01:00:35,778
Jeez, what's the break-even point, then?

911
01:00:37,029 --> 01:00:40,366
Why would you invest so much money
in a piece of crap like that?

912
01:00:40,450 --> 01:00:42,285
It has no substance.

913
01:00:43,202 --> 01:00:47,206
They're doing everything they can
to cover it up with mise-en-scène.

914
01:00:47,290 --> 01:00:49,792
My goodness.

915
01:00:49,876 --> 01:00:52,295
Now, mise-en-scène sucks too.

916
01:00:53,713 --> 01:00:57,800
And there isn't a single heartfelt line.

917
01:00:57,884 --> 01:01:02,805
It's like the writer racked their brains
and desperately forced out some words.

918
01:01:02,889 --> 01:01:03,723
Jeez.

919
01:01:03,806 --> 01:01:05,933
Hey, say something to Director An.

920
01:01:06,017 --> 01:01:07,310
Does anyone tell him this?

921
01:01:07,393 --> 01:01:08,478
You two are friends, right?

922
01:01:08,561 --> 01:01:09,812
Tell him already!

923
01:01:10,563 --> 01:01:13,733
This is why
I plaster the internet with posts.

924
01:01:13,816 --> 01:01:15,401
It's because no one says anything!

925
01:01:16,194 --> 01:01:17,153
I'm sorry.

926
01:01:17,236 --> 01:01:19,447
The other company
already persuaded the director,

927
01:01:20,072 --> 01:01:21,491
so there's nothing I can do.

928
01:01:22,074 --> 01:01:23,785
I'll have to return the grant.

929
01:01:25,286 --> 01:01:29,040
There's an option to move forward
with the runner-up's screenplay.

930
01:01:29,123 --> 01:01:31,501
If the winner declines the grant,

931
01:01:31,584 --> 01:01:35,797
we can award it to the runner-up,
and there are no procedural issues.

932
01:01:36,756 --> 01:01:39,091
Would you like to read their screenplay?

933
01:01:40,092 --> 01:01:42,053
It's called Weather Maker.

934
01:01:43,971 --> 01:01:47,266
Stop overdoing it
with visual effects and whatnot

935
01:01:47,350 --> 01:01:49,435
and focus more on the props!

936
01:01:49,519 --> 01:01:51,395
What if the actor suddenly opens a drawer?

937
01:01:51,479 --> 01:01:53,523
It could happen, right?

938
01:01:53,606 --> 01:01:55,900
WEATHER MAKER

939
01:02:04,075 --> 01:02:04,909
What do you think?

940
01:02:06,661 --> 01:02:07,870
There's a lot going on.

941
01:02:10,623 --> 01:02:11,916
Do you think it'll make its money back?

942
01:02:13,835 --> 01:02:15,169
I understand your concern.

943
01:02:17,296 --> 01:02:19,173
Then let's just drop it.

944
01:02:20,925 --> 01:02:21,884
Okay.

945
01:02:21,968 --> 01:02:24,846
For the love of god,
stuff the drawers on set!

946
01:02:24,929 --> 01:02:27,473
Who lives in a house with empty drawers?

947
01:02:37,358 --> 01:02:38,234
You know what?

948
01:02:40,319 --> 01:02:42,280
I've had enough.

949
01:02:43,197 --> 01:02:44,615
Are you kicking me out again?

950
01:02:46,033 --> 01:02:46,868
I'm not leaving.

951
01:02:47,451 --> 01:02:49,078
Go ahead and try dragging me out.

952
01:02:52,123 --> 01:02:56,794
You've never stepped into the ring
and gotten your ass kicked.

953
01:02:56,878 --> 01:02:59,839
That's why you just sit there
trashing other people's films.

954
01:03:00,339 --> 01:03:04,760
He won't stop until he enters the ring
and gets beaten into a pulp.

955
01:03:06,137 --> 01:03:06,971
I don't care

956
01:03:08,180 --> 01:03:10,141
if it costs me billions of won.

957
01:03:11,434 --> 01:03:13,102
I'm going to teach this bastard a lesson.

958
01:03:17,064 --> 01:03:19,317
Hey, it's getting bad here. Go home.

959
01:03:19,400 --> 01:03:21,193
-Why? I don't want to.
-Just go.

960
01:03:21,277 --> 01:03:22,278
Hello, it's me.

961
01:03:23,905 --> 01:03:25,281
Instead of Ma Jae-yeong…

962
01:03:27,909 --> 01:03:30,453
we'll go with the runner-up's screenplay.

963
01:03:31,078 --> 01:03:33,331
Yes, Weather Maker by Hwang Dong-man.

964
01:03:38,127 --> 01:03:39,587
I'm going to let it fail.

965
01:03:40,713 --> 01:03:41,881
I'm going to let it fail completely,

966
01:03:42,506 --> 01:03:44,508
but I'll take comfort
in teaching someone a lesson.

967
01:03:44,592 --> 01:03:45,426
No way.

968
01:03:45,509 --> 01:03:47,720
No, I'm serious.
We're producing Hwang Dong-man's work.

969
01:03:48,930 --> 01:03:50,640
Yes, I'll see you tomorrow.

970
01:03:57,271 --> 01:03:58,105
You…

971
01:04:00,191 --> 01:04:01,400
are so dead.

972
01:04:02,985 --> 01:04:04,070
Step into the ring…

973
01:04:06,113 --> 01:04:07,365
and get your ass kicked.

974
01:04:11,535 --> 01:04:12,745
You can't run away.

975
01:04:26,550 --> 01:04:28,219
-Producer Kim!
-Yes?

976
01:04:28,302 --> 01:04:29,220
Put together a production team.

977
01:04:29,804 --> 01:04:30,638
Sorry?

978
01:04:49,323 --> 01:04:50,950
WE ARE ALL TRYING HERE

979
01:05:10,970 --> 01:05:12,346
This year's winner!

980
01:05:12,430 --> 01:05:14,515
We need to push Hwang Dong-man
to his limits.

981
01:05:14,598 --> 01:05:18,519
He can tremble in fear,
give up, and fall flat on his face.

982
01:05:18,602 --> 01:05:20,021
Who's Yeong-sil?

983
01:05:20,104 --> 01:05:21,188
It sounds like a pseudonym.

984
01:05:22,106 --> 01:05:25,026
Tell Yeong-sil I want to meet her.

985
01:05:25,735 --> 01:05:26,819
Did you borrow from a loan shark?

986
01:05:26,902 --> 01:05:29,572
Looks like this bastard
came into some money.

987
01:05:29,655 --> 01:05:31,699
He'll never complete a film at this rate.

988
01:05:31,782 --> 01:05:33,576
Good luck, Dong-man!

989
01:05:33,659 --> 01:05:35,870
Hwang Dong-man is really something.

990
01:05:36,454 --> 01:05:37,913
I'm so embarrassed by who I am right now

991
01:05:37,997 --> 01:05:40,166
that becoming
a slightly less embarrassing person

992
01:05:40,249 --> 01:05:41,500
is my purpose in life!

993
01:05:43,961 --> 01:05:48,966
Subtitle translation by: Jenny Kim
